When prompted to debug a module, follow these steps in order:

1. Initial Setup and Analysis:
   - Verify the module directory structure is correct
   - Check for presence of all required files:
     - [modulename].sv
     - test_[modulename].py
     - Makefile
     - README.md
   - Review the test plan in [modulename]_tests.txt if available

2. First Run and Log Analysis:
   - Run `make clean && make` to get a fresh build
   - Examine sim.log for:
     - Compilation errors
     - Test failures
     - Parameter mismatches
     - Timing violations
   - Document all failures and their locations

3. Testbench-First Debugging (Priority):
   a) Parameter Verification:
      - Check if testbench parameters match DUT parameters
      - Verify parameter passing in Makefile
      - Ensure PLUSARGS/COMPILE_ARGS are correctly set
      - Test with both default and non-default parameters

   b) Reset Sequence Analysis:
      - Verify reset timing in testbench
      - Check reset assertion/deassertion timing
      - Ensure proper clock cycles between reset operations
      - Verify reset value propagation

   c) Signal Timing Verification:
      - Check clock setup and timing
      - Verify signal propagation delays
      - Ensure proper edge alignment
      - Check for race conditions

   d) Test Structure Review:
      - Verify test independence
      - Check for proper test sequencing
      - Ensure adequate test coverage
      - Verify edge case handling

4. DUT Debugging (Only after testbench is verified):
   a) Reset Behavior:
      - Verify asynchronous reset implementation
      - Check reset value assignments
      - Ensure proper reset state transitions

   b) Signal Handling:
      - Verify input/output connections
      - Check signal widths and types
      - Ensure proper clock domain handling
      - Verify combinational logic

   c) State Machine Analysis:
      - Check state transitions
      - Verify state encoding
      - Ensure proper state initialization
      - Check for unreachable states

5. Iterative Testing Process:
   a) Make one change at a time
   b) Run tests after each change
   c) Document changes and results
   d) Revert changes that don't improve the situation

6. Common Issues to Check:
   - Parameter mismatches between testbench and DUT
   - Reset timing and behavior
   - Clock domain crossing issues
   - Signal width mismatches
   - Race conditions
   - Uninitialized signals
   - Incorrect edge sensitivity

7. Debugging Guidelines:
   - Always start with testbench verification
   - Make minimal changes to fix issues
   - Document all changes and their rationale
   - Verify fixes don't introduce new issues
   - Use systematic approach to isolate problems
   - Consider both functional and timing issues

8. Success Criteria:
   - All tests pass
   - No compilation warnings
   - No timing violations
   - Proper parameter handling
   - Correct reset behavior
   - Expected signal timing
   - Clean simulation log

9. Documentation:
   - Update README.md with any behavioral changes
   - Document any parameter changes
   - Update test descriptions if needed
   - Note any timing requirements
   - Document reset behavior

10. Final Verification:
    - Run full test suite
    - Check simulation log
    - Verify parameter handling
    - Confirm reset behavior
    - Validate timing requirements